nity." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  Polynomials:  Local extreme values and monotonicit
y.  Beyond information of the type gathered above about intercepts and
 signs of a polynomial,  other important information can be determined
 from the so called \"critical points\" of a polynomial.  The critical
 points of a polynomial are the intercepts of its derivative.  Since t
he derivative of a function at a point represents the slope of the tan
gent line to the graph of the that function at the point, then the int
ercepts of the derivative are places where the the tangent lines to th
e function are flat, i.e., are horizontal lines.  At such places the g
raph is neither increasing nor decreasing.  Elsewhere the graph must b
e either increasing or decreasing.  For a polynomial, local extreme va
lues (local maximums or local minimums) must occur at the intercepts o
f the derivative.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 80 "     The follwing features are important in analyzing t
he graph of a polynomial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "     f.   critical points of the function" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "                      For a polynomial th
ese are the intercepts of the derivative of the polynomial" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     g.    local maximum points of the graph of a
 function y = f(x)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 274 "                  \+
    These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which the \+
y-value is locally the largest value of the function.  Nearby values o
n the graph are lower.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (x,
y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local minimum points of the graph of a function
 y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "                      Thes
e are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which the y-value \+
is locally the smallest value of the function.  Nearby values on the g
raph are higher.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (x,y) mus
t be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
108 "     i.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function wher
e the values of the function are increasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 249 "                       Those regions where the graph rises as \+
the graph is traversed from left to right.  For a continuous function,
 and in particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the c
ritical points and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 108 "     j.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the func
tion where the values of the function are decreasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those regions where the graph f
alls as the graph is traversed from left to right.  For a continuous f
unction, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded \+
by the critical points and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 275 "For each of the fol
lowing polynomials,  provide a graph of the polynomial.  Choose a rang
e that will optimally represent the features of the graph.  Include th
e graph of the deriviative of the polynomial on the plot.   Plot the f
unction in red and the derviative in green.   " }{TEXT 269 4 "Also" }
{TEXT -1 89 ", for each polynomial find each of the above ten graphcia
l characteristics (a.  thru j.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
